Solution: Plugins

Alberto Miño
on Apr 23

Great challenge!
I based my solution on your plugin architecture video:

*** plugin_manager.py ***

LUGINS_DIRECTORY = 'plugins'

class ModuleInterface(Protocol):
"""Represents a module interface"""
@staticmethod
def process_payment() -> None:
...

@staticmethod
def register(payment_handlers: dict[str, Callable[[Decimal], None]]) -> None:
...

def process_plugins(directory: str) -> Iterable:
for _, _, files in os.walk(PLUGINS_DIRECTORY):
return map(lambda x: x.split(".")[0], files)
return []

def import_module(name: str) -> ModuleInterface:
return importlib.import_module(name) # type: ignore

def load_plugins(payment_handlers: dict[str, Callable]) -> None:
for plugin in process_plugins(PLUGINS_DIRECTORY):
process_payment = import_module(f'{PLUGINS_DIRECTORY}.{plugin}')
process_payment.register(payment_handlers)

Payment methods in plugin folder looks almost the same:

from decimal import Decimal
from typing import Callable

def process_payment(total: Decimal) -> None:
username = input("Please enter your PayPal username: ")
password = input("Please enter your PayPal password: ")
password_masked = len(password) * "*"
print(
f"Processing PayPal payment of ${total:.2f} with username {username} and password {password_masked}..."
)

def register(payment_handlers: dict[str, Callable[[Decimal], None]]) -> None:
payment_handlers['paypal'] = process_payment

And finally in main module (just describing parts I've changed):

PaymentHandlerFn = Callable[[Decimal], None]
PAYMENT_HANDLERS: dict[str, PaymentHandlerFn] = {}

def handle_payment(total: Decimal) -> None:
payment_methods = [method for method in PAYMENT_HANDLERS]
payment_type = input(
f"What payment method would you like to use? {payment_methods}"
)

if payment_type in PAYMENT_HANDLERS:
# Process the payment
PAYMENT_HANDLERS[payment_type](total)
else:
print(f"Payment type '{payment_type}' is not valid!")

# Loading payment types
plugin_manager.load_plugins(PAYMENT_HANDLERS)
handle_payment(cart.total)

Off course I like more your solution but was really interesting how I've come up with one that works well too :)

Thanks!

Nice! this one was definitely pushing the boundaries compared to what i typically come up with to handle that type of complexity. great challenge! the Protocol defining what to expect in any of the plugin modules was a nice twist :)

when re-implementing Arjan's proposal, i found myself tempted to wrap most of the functions written in plugins_manager.py into a PluginManager class. that way i feel we rely less on that PLUGINS dictionary that's implicitly relied on by all of those functions without appearing anywhere in the main.py code.
@Arjan, is there a reason you went with a functional approach in this case?

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Jan 15

Hi Sylvain, glad to hear you enjoyed the challenge :). Regarding functional vs object-oriented, I typically start with a functional nowadays, but an object-oriented approach is not wrong per se :). I try to avoid "XXXManager" type classes since you would normally only create a single instance of those, and in that case, it makes more sense to me to use a module.

Hi @Arjan,

Thank you very much for putting this challenge together.

I have a question concerning when to use strategy pattern VS factory pattern. Are you suggesting that one should be using the factory pattern whenever the number of interchangeable algorithms we are dealing with is prone to grow ?

REPLY
Aïman S.
on Sep 8, 2023

Asking about this as I actually replicated refactoring from "The power of the pluging" tutorial https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iCE1bDoit9Q&ab_channel=ArjanCodes. This leads me to create a factory and then to use the pluging for this challenge. Not sure if that was the simplest approach.

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Sep 12, 2023

Hi Aiman, you're welcome! Strategy and Factory have very different purposes. Strategy is concerned with allowing for interchangeable algorithms. Factory is concerned with allowing to create all sorts of different objects that follow a given structure. So, if you need to switch algorithms, then Strategy is a great choice regardless of the number of algorithms. If you need a mechanism to create many objects without knowing what specific objects you're creating, then Factory is a good option.

REPLY
Aïman S.
on Sep 12, 2023

Thank you for your reply @Arjan, this actually helps a lot

Would you help me understand further the idea through this example from data science: if we have to build a library/package with a bunch of algorithms (GBM, SVM, leNet for example, which let's say will have the same structure: .fit, .predict) I guess that the best way to go is the strategy pattern, but when I think about a way to combine them and not necessarily use them interchangeable the factory pattern seems to fit better.

What do you think please?

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Sep 18, 2023

Hi Aiman, that would indeed be a good use case for the Strategy pattern. If you want to supply different collections of algorithms, then the Factory pattern is a good choice because you can then group those algorithms as methods and let the factory create those objects.
